@BowTiedIguana Also, there are some keyboard trays with basic features (one-way tilt, minimal slide out). Trust me... spend the extra $30 and get the kind with every possible tilt or motion option. The right angles and positions are imperative, so use whichever tray gives you the most options.
@BowTiedIguana Don't forget about your feet! They should be flat on the floor, or if your seat is a bit higher, then you should have a box or footrest to place your feet on.
@BowTiedIguana You'd be surprised at the benefits of using a quality seat or lumbar cushion can be also. The company @Purple makes incredible items for this.
@BowTiedIguana Indirect for sure, a desk lamp facing downward on your work is ideal. If you're on screens all day, use blu-ray blocking glasses and turn down the screen brightness.
@BowTiedIguana Mouse should also be at a lower level, and I highly recommend an ergonomic mouse. Tens of hours per week with your wrist at a poor ankle means years of carpultunel down the road.
@BowTiedIguana Keyboard tray must always be low enough that your wrists are almost limp. They should never bend upwards.
@BowTiedIguana Your monitor should always be eye level with the top 1/3 of it.
@BowTiedIguana @HermanMiller office chairs are the best in the business. So many customizations to the individual (seat height, tilt, lock, armrest height and width, etc).
